# WordPress/PHP Project Rules

> Источник: https://developer.wordpress.org/coding-standards/wordpress-coding-standards/php/

You are an expert in WordPress development, PHP coding standards, and WordPress best practices.

## WordPress Coding Standards

### PHP Syntax
- Always use full PHP tags: `<?php ... ?>` (never shorthand `<? ?>`)
- Remove trailing whitespace at end of lines
- Omit closing PHP tag at end of files (prevents trailing whitespace issues)
- Use single quotes when not evaluating variables, double quotes when evaluating

### Naming Conventions
- Variables and functions: `lowercase_with_underscores` (never camelCase)
- Classes: `Capitalized_Words_With_Underscores` (e.g., `WP_Error`, `Walker_Category`)
- Constants: `ALL_UPPERCASE_WITH_UNDERSCORES`
- Files: `lowercase-with-hyphens.php`
- Class files: `class-capitalized-words.php` (e.g., `class-wp-error.php`)

### Formatting
- Use real tabs (not spaces) for indentation
- One space on both sides of operators: `$foo === $bar`
- Always use braces for control structures, even single statements
- Use Yoda conditions for comparisons: `if ( 'value' === $variable )`
- Use `elseif`, not `else if`
- Arrays: Use long array syntax `array( 1, 2, 3 )` (not short syntax `[ 1, 2, 3 ]`)

### Object-Oriented Programming
- One class/interface/trait per file
- Always declare visibility (`public`, `protected`, `private`)
- Never use `var` keyword (use visibility modifiers)
- Trait use statements at top of class with proper spacing
- Object instantiation: Always use parentheses `new Class_Name()`

### Functions
- Use descriptive names: `function_name_with_underscores()`
- Prefer string values over booleans for function flags (readability)
- Avoid using `extract()` function (security and maintainability)
- Don't use `eval()` or `create_function()` (security risk)
- Avoid error control operator `@` (use proper error handling)

### Database Queries
- Avoid direct database queries - use WordPress functions when available
- Use `$wpdb->prepare()` for all SQL queries with user input
- Always escape output: `esc_html()`, `esc_attr()`, `esc_url()`, `esc_js()`
- Always sanitize input: `sanitize_text_field()`, `sanitize_email()`, etc.
- Validate data before using it

### Security Best Practices
- Never trust user input - always validate and sanitize
- Use nonces for forms and AJAX requests
- Check user capabilities with `current_user_can()`
- Escape all output: HTML, attributes, URLs, JavaScript
- Use prepared statements for database queries
- Don't expose sensitive data in error messages

### WordPress-Specific Patterns
- Use WordPress hooks (actions and filters) for extensibility
- Prefix all functions, classes, and constants with unique prefix
- Use `plugin_dir_path()` and `plugin_dir_url()` for paths
- Use `__()` and `_e()` for translatable strings (with text domain)
- Use WordPress conditional tags: `is_admin()`, `is_front_page()`, etc.
- Use `get_option()`, `update_option()`, `delete_option()` for settings

### Headless WordPress Specific
- Use WPGraphQL for API endpoints (not REST API)
- Create custom post types for content organization
- Use Advanced Custom Fields (ACF) for flexible content structure
- Implement proper GraphQL schema extensions
- Use WordPress hooks to extend WPGraphQL schema
- Cache GraphQL queries appropriately

### Performance
- Use WordPress transients for caching
- Implement proper pagination for queries
- Use `WP_Query` efficiently with specific fields
- Avoid querying in loops (use `pre_get_posts` filter)
- Use object caching for expensive operations
- Optimize database queries (use indexes, avoid LIKE with leading wildcard)

### Code Organization
- Use namespaces for plugins (e.g., `Vendor\Plugin_Name`)
- Implement autoloading with Composer when possible
- Separate concerns: models, views, controllers
- Use dependency injection for testability
- Follow WordPress file structure conventions
